999,9" is <em>four nines fine</em> <span role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote nav=
igation-not-searchable crossreference">(see: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Fineness#Gold" title=3D"Fineness">Fineness =C2=A7&nbsp;Gold</a>)=
</span>, meaning it is pure to 999.9 parts in 1,000 (<em>i.e.</em><span sty=
le=3D"visibility:hidden; color:transparent; padding-left:2px">=E2=80=8D</sp=
an>99.99% pure)</figcaption></figure>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Ingots_of_Ge,_Fe,_Al,_Re,_Os,_one_troy_ounce_=
each_(2).jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wiki=
media.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/14/Ingots_of_Ge%2C_Fe%2C_Al%2C_Re%2C_Os=
%2C_one_troy_ounce_each_%282%29.jpg/250px-Ingots_of_Ge%2C_Fe%2C_Al%2C_Re%2C=
_Os%2C_one_troy_ounce_each_%282%29.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" he=
ight=3D"181" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"3672" data-file-h=
eight=3D"2657"></a><figcaption>One-troy-ounce (480&nbsp;gr; 31&nbsp;g) samp=
les of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Germanium" title=3D"Germani=
um">germanium</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iron" title=3D"=
Iron">iron</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aluminium" title=
=3D"Aluminium">aluminium</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhen=
ium" title=3D"Rhenium">rhenium</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Osmium" title=3D"Osmium">osmium</a>. The differences in size are due t=
o differences in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Density" title=3D=
"Density">density</a>.</figcaption></figure>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:1000oz.silver.bullion.bar.underneath.jpg" cla=
ss=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikiped=
ia/commons/thumb/e/e2/1000oz.silver.bullion.bar.underneath.jpg/250px-1000oz=
.silver.bullion.bar.underneath.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=
=3D"158" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1014" data-file-heigh=
t=3D"642"></a><figcaption>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Good_D=
elivery" title=3D"Good Delivery">Good Delivery</a> silver bar weighing 1,00=
0 troy ounces (83 troy pounds; 31&nbsp;kg)</figcaption></figure>
<p><b>Troy weight</b> is a system of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Physical_unit" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Physical unit">units</a> o=
f <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mass" title=3D"Mass">mass</a> wh=
ose origin is uncertain.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-HallockWade1906_1-0" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troy_weight#cite_note-Ha=
llockWade1906-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> By far the most common troy unit is the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troy_weight#Troy_ounce">troy ounce (oz t)=
</a>, the standard mass unit for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P=
recious_metals" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Precious metals">precious me=
tals</a> in industry and in trade; it equals 31.1034768 <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gram" title=3D"Gram">grams</a>. The troy weight units=
 are the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grain_(unit)" title=3D"Gr=
ain (unit)">grain</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pennywe=
ight" title=3D"Pennyweight">pennyweight</a> (24 grains), the troy ounce (20=
 pennyweights), and the troy pound (12 troy ounces). The troy grain is equa=
l to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grain_(unit)" title=3D"Gr=
ain (unit)">grain</a> unit of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Avoirdupois" title=3D"Avoirdupois">avoirdupois</a> and <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apothecaries%27_system" title=3D"Apothecaries' system"=
>apothecaries'</a> systems, but the troy ounce is heavier than the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ounce#International_avoirdupois_ounce" ti=
tle=3D"Ounce">avoirdupois ounce</a>, and the troy pound is lighter than the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pound_(mass)#Avoirdupois_pound" t=
itle=3D"Pound (mass)">avoirdupois pound</a>.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Etymology">Etymology</h2><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTroy_weight&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Etymology"><span>edit</=
span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Troy weight is generally supposed to take its name from the French marke=
t town of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troyes" title=3D"Troyes"=
>Troyes</a> where English merchants traded at least as early as the early <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/9th_century" title=3D"9th century">=
9th century</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-OED3troy2_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troy_weight#cite_note-OED3troy2-2"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Troy_weight#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The name <i>troy</i> is=
 first attested in 1390, describing the weight of a platter, in an account =
of the travels in Europe of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/He=
nry_IV_of_England#Relationship_with_Richard_II" title=3D"Henry IV of Englan=
d">Earl of Derby</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-OED3troy2_2-1" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troy_weight#cite_note-OED3troy2-2=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troy_weight#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Moore_Watson" title=
=3D"Charles Moore Watson">Charles Moore Watson</a> (1844=E2=80=931916) prop=
oses an alternative etymology:  <i>The Assize of Weights and Measures</i> (=
also known as <span title=3D"Latin-language text"><i lang=3D"la"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weights_and_Measures_Acts_(UK)#Acts_of_Parli=
ament" title=3D"Weights and Measures Acts (UK)">Tractatus de Ponderibus et =
Mensuris</a></i></span>), one of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Statutes_of_uncertain_date" title=3D"Statutes of uncertain date">statute=
s of uncertain date</a> from the reign of either <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Henry_III_of_England" title=3D"Henry III of England">Henry I=
II</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_I_of_England" tit=
le=3D"Edward I of England">Edward I</a>, thus before 1307, specifies "<span=
 title=3D"Latin-language text"><i lang=3D"la">troni ponderacionem</i></span=
>"=E2=80=94which the Public Record Commissioners translate as "troy weight"=
.  The word <span title=3D"Latin-language text"><i lang=3D"la">tron</i></sp=
an> refers to markets.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" =
style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=
=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (March 2024)">citation=
 needed</span></a></i>]</sup> Wright's <i>The English Dialect Dictionary</i=
> lists the word <i>troi</i> as meaning a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Weighing_scale#Mechanical_balances" title=3D"Weighing scale">balanc=
e</a>, related to the alternate form 'tron' which also means market or the =
place of weighing. From this, Watson suggests that 'troy' derives from the =
manner of weighing by balance precious goods such as bullion or drugs; in c=
ontrast to the word 'avoirdupois' used to describe bulk goods such as corn =
or coal, sometimes weighed in ancient times by a kind of <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steelyard_balance" title=3D"Steelyard balance">steel=
yard</a> called the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Auncel" title=
=3D"Auncel">auncel</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-CMW1910_5-0" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troy_weight#cite_note-CMW1910-5">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup>
</p><p>Troy weight referred to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/English_units_of_measurement#Troy_and_Tower" title=3D"English units of mea=
surement">Tower system</a>; the earliest reference to the modern troy weigh=
ts is in 1414.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-CMW1910_5-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troy_weight#cite_note-CMW1910-5"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p><sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Troy_weight#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTroy_weight&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</span><=
/a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The origin of the troy weight system is unknown. Although the name proba=
bly comes from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Champagne_fairs=
" title=3D"Champagne fairs">Champagne fairs</a> at <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Troyes" title=3D"Troyes">Troyes</a>, in northeastern Franc=
e.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Troy_weight#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> English troy weights were ne=
arly identical to the troy weight system of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Bremen" title=3D"Bremen">Bremen</a>. (The Bremen troy ounce had a=
 mass of 480.8 British Imperial grains.)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1977zupko_8-0" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troy_weight#ci=
te_note-1977zupko-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Many aspects of the troy weight system were indirectly derived from =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roman_currency" title=3D"Roman=
 currency">Roman monetary system</a>. Before they used coins, <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Rome" title=3D"Ancient Rome">early Roma=
ns</a> used bronze bars of varying weights as currency. An <span title=3D"L=
atin-language text"><i lang=3D"la"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Aes_grave" title=3D"Aes grave">aes grave</a></i></span> ("heavy bronze") w=
eighed one <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pound_(mass)" title=3D"=
Pound (mass)">pound</a>. One twelfth of an <span title=3D"Latin-language te=
xt"><i lang=3D"la">aes grave</i></span> was called an <span title=3D"Latin-=
language text"><i lang=3D"la"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anci=
ent_Roman_units_of_measurement#Weight" title=3D"Ancient Roman units of meas=
urement">uncia</a></i></span>, or in English, an "ounce". Before the adopti=
on of the metric system, many systems of troy weights were in use in variou=
s parts of Europe, among them Holland troy, Paris troy, etc.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-Kelly_9-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Troy_weight#cite_note-Kelly-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Their values varied from one an=
other by up to several percentage points. Troy weights were first used in E=
ngland in the 15th century and were made official for gold and silver in 15=
27.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-HallockWade1906_1-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troy_weight#cite_note-HallockWade1906-1"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> The British Imperial system of weights and measures (also known as <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imperial_units" title=3D"Imperial u=
nits">imperial units</a>) was established in 1824, prior to which the troy =
weight system was a subset of pre-imperial <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/English_units_of_measurement" title=3D"English units of measuremen=
t">English units</a>.
</p><p>The troy ounce in modern use is essentially the same as the British =
Imperial troy ounce (1824=E2=80=931971), adopted as an official weight stan=
dard for United States coinage by act of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/United_States_Congress" title=3D"United States Congress">Congress</a=
> on May 19, 1828.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troy_weight#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The Briti=
sh Imperial troy ounce (known more commonly simply as the imperial troy oun=
ce) was based on, and virtually identical with, the pre-1824 British troy o=
unce and the pre-1707 English troy ounce. (1824 was the year the British Im=
perial system of weights and measures was adopted; 1707 was the year of the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acts_of_Union_1707" title=3D"Acts=
 of Union 1707">Act of Union</a> which created the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Kingdom_of_Great_Britain" title=3D"Kingdom of Great Britai=
n">Kingdom of Great Britain</a>.) Troy ounces have been used in England sin=
ce the early 15th century, and the English troy ounce was officially adopte=
d for coinage in 1527. Before that time, various sorts of troy ounces were =
in use on the continent.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1977zupko_8-1" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troy_weight#cite_note-1977zupk=
o-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p><p>The troy ounce and grain were also part of the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apothecaries%27_system" title=3D"Apothecaries' system">=
apothecaries' system</a>. This was long used in medicine, but has been larg=
ely replaced by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metric_system"=
 title=3D"Metric system">metric system</a> (milligrams).<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-dictionary.com_11-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Troy_weight#cite_note-dictionary.com-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The only troy =
weight in widespread use is the British Imperial troy ounce and its America=
n counterpart. Both are based on a grain of 0.06479891&nbsp;gram (exact, by=
 definition), with 480 grains to a troy ounce (compared with <span class=3D=
"frac">437<span class=3D"sr-only">+</span><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=
=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</span></span> grains for an ounce avoirdupois).=
 The British Empire abolished the 12-ounce troy pound in the 19th century. =
It has been retained, though rarely used, in the American system. Larger am=
ounts of precious metals are conventionally counted in hundreds or thousand=
s of troy ounces, or in kilograms.
</p><p>Troy ounces have been and are still often used in precious metal mar=
kets in countries that otherwise use <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/International_System_of_Units" title=3D"International System of Units">I=
nternational System of Units</a> (SI).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troy_weight#cite_note-12"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troy_weight#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/People%27s_Bank_of_China" title=3D"Peo=
ple's Bank of China">People's Bank of China</a>&nbsp;=E2=80=93  which had b=
een using troy measurements in minting <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Chinese_Gold_Panda#Revised_weights" title=3D"Chinese Gold Panda">Gold =
Pandas</a> since 1982&nbsp;=E2=80=93  from 2016 specifies Chinese bullion c=
oins in an integer numbers of grams.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troy_weight#cite_note-14"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Units_of_measurement">Units=
 of measurement</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DTroy_weight&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: U=
nits of measurement"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
cket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Comparison_of_pounds.svg" class=3D"mw-file-de=
scription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb=
/0/0a/Comparison_of_pounds.svg/250px-Comparison_of_pounds.svg.png" decoding=
=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"63" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-=
width=3D"512" data-file-height=3D"128"></a><figcaption>Chart comparing the =
mass (in grams) of tower, Troy, merchant, avoirdupois and London pounds. Ea=
ch colored block represents one of that system's ounces (gold=3DTroy, blue=
=3D avoirdupois, purple=3Dtower)</figcaption></figure>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Troy_pound_(lb_t)"><span id=
=3D"Troy_pound_.28lb_t.29"></span>Troy pound (lb t) <span class=3D"anchor" =
id=3D"Troy_pound"></span></h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DTroy_weight&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit =
section: Troy pound (lb t)"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:TroyPoundEngraving.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-desc=
ription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/04/Tr=
oyPoundEngraving.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"232" height=3D"350" class=
=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"232" data-file-height=3D"350"></a><=
figcaption>The standard British troy pound manufactured in 1758; it bears t=
he abbreviation <span class=3D"nounderlines" style=3D"border: 1px solid var=
(--border-color-muted,#ddd); color: var(--color-base,#202122); background-c=
olor: var( --background-color-neutral-subtle, #fdfdfd); padding: 1px 1px;">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E2%84%94" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"=E2=84=94">=E2=84=94</a></span> ("pound") and the letter "T" for tr=
oy.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The troy pound (lb t) consists of twelve troy ounces<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
Perth_Mint_15-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Troy_weight#cite_note-Perth_Mint-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and thus is <span style=
=3D"white-space: nowrap">5<span style=3D"margin-left: 0.25em">760</span></s=
pan> grains (<span style=3D"white-space: nowrap">373.241<span style=3D"marg=
in-left: 0.25em">72</span></span> grams). (An avoirdupois pound is approxim=
ately 21.53% heavier, at <span style=3D"white-space: nowrap">7<span style=
=3D"margin-left: 0.25em">000</span></span> grains (<span style=3D"white-spa=
ce: nowrap">453.592<span style=3D"margin-left: 0.25em">37</span></span> gra=
ms), and consists of sixteen avoirdupois ounces.)
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Troy_ounce_(oz_t)"><span id=
=3D"Troy_ounce_.28oz_t.29"></span>Troy ounce (oz t) <span class=3D"anchor" =
id=3D"Troy_ounce"></span></h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DTroy_weight&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit =
section: Troy ounce (oz t)"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A troy ounce is 480 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grain_(unit=
)" title=3D"Grain (unit)">grains</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Perth_Mint_15-1" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troy_weight#cit=
e_note-Perth_Mint-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Since the implementation of the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_yard_and_pound" title=3D"In=
ternational yard and pound">international yard and pound</a> agreement of 1=
 July 1959, the grain measure is defined as precisely <span class=3D"nowrap=
"><span data-sort-value=3D"7001647989100000000=E2=99=A0"></span>64.798<span=
 style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">91</span>&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Milligram" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Milligram">milligrams<=
/a></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-NIST_16-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troy_weight#cite_note-NIST-16"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup =
class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page / location: C-19">:=E2=80=8A=
C-19=E2=80=8A</span></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-nbs447_17-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troy_weight#cite_note-nbs447-1=
7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> Thus one troy ounce =3D 480 grains =C3=97 <span style=3D"whi=
te-space: nowrap">0.064<span style=3D"margin-left: 0.25em">798</span><span =
style=3D"margin-left: 0.25em">91</span></span> grams/grain =3D <span style=
=3D"white-space: nowrap">31.103<span style=3D"margin-left: 0.25em">476</spa=
n><span style=3D"margin-left: 0.25em">80</span></span> grams. Since the oun=
ce avoirdupois is defined as 437.5 grains, a troy ounce is exactly <link re=
l=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r11549410=
27"><span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">480</span>=E2=81=84<span class=
=3D"den">437.5</span></span> =3D <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style"=
 href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac"><span cla=
ss=3D"num">192</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">175</span></span> or abou=
t 1.09714 ounces avoirdupois or about 9.7% more. The troy ounce for trading=
 precious metals is considered to be sufficiently approximated by 31.10&nbs=
p;g in EU directive 80/181/EEC.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-80/181/EER_18-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troy_weight#cite_no=
te-80/181/EER-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The troy ounce is the only troy unit allowed =
in trade in the United Kingdom, and only for precious metals, since the imp=
lementation of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weights_and_Mea=
sures_Acts_(UK)#Metric_units_of_measure" title=3D"Weights and Measures Acts=
 (UK)">Weights and Measures Act of 1985</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troy_weight#cite_no=
te-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The Dutch troy system is based on a mark of 8 ounces, the ounce of 2=
0 engels (pennyweights), the engel of 32 as. The mark was rated as 3,798 tr=
oy grains or 246.084 grams. The divisions are identical to the tower system=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Kelly_9-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Troy_weight#cite_note-Kelly-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Pennyweight_(dwt)"><span id=
=3D"Pennyweight_.28dwt.29"></span>Pennyweight (dwt)</h3><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTroy_weight&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;s=
ection=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Pennyweight (dwt)"><span>edit</span></a>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pennyweight" title=3D"Penny=
weight">pennyweight</a> symbol is <i>dwt</i>. One pennyweight weighs 24 gra=
ins, and 20 pennyweights make one troy ounce.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Perth_Mint=
_15-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troy_we=
ight#cite_note-Perth_Mint-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Because there were 12 troy ounces=
 in the old troy pound, there would have been 240 pennyweights to the pound=
 (mass)&nbsp;=E2=80=93  just as there were 240 pennies in the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pound_sterling#Anglo-Saxon,_c_800_CE" title=3D"=
Pound sterling">original pound-sterling</a>. However, prior to 1526, the En=
glish <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pound_sterling" title=3D"Pou=
nd sterling">pound sterling</a> was based on the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Tower_pound" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tower pound">tow=
er pound</a>, which is <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"m=
w-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num"=
>15</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">16</span></span> of a troy pound. Th=
e <i>d</i> in <i>dwt</i> stands for <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Denarius" title=3D"Denarius">denarius</a></i>, the ancient Roman coin =
that equates loosely to a penny. The symbol <i>d</i> for penny can be recog=
nized in the form of British pre-decimal pennies, in which pounds, shilling=
s, and pence were indicated using the symbols <i>=C2=A3</i>, <i>s</i>, and =
<i>d</i>, respectively.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Troy_grain">Troy grain</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTroy_weight&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Troy grain"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grain_(mass)" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Grain (mass)">Grain (mass)</a></div>
<p>There is no specific 'troy grain'. All <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Imperial_unit" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Imperial unit">Imperi=
al systems</a> use the same measure of mass called a grain (historically of=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barley" title=3D"Barley">barley</=
a>), each weighing <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-da=
ta:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">1</=
span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">7000</span></span> of an avoirdupois poun=
d (and thus a little under 65 milligrams).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troy_weight#cite_note-2=
0"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>a<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Mint_masses">Mint masses</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTroy_weight&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Mint masses"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Mint masses, also known as <i>moneyers' masses</i>, were legalized by Ac=
t of Parliament dated 17 July 1649 entitled <i>An Act touching the monies a=
nd coins of England</i>. A grain is 20 mites, a mite is 24 droits, a droit =
is 20 perits, a perit is 24 blanks.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Britain)1891_21-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troy_weight#cit=
e_note-Britain)1891-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Miege_22-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troy_weight#cite_no=
te-Miege-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
